Saoul of corruption
My friend Boris was going to leave my place, drunk.
I therefore suggested to him not to drive.
He asked me why.
"You have drunk," I said to him, "don't you fear the police?"
Boris replied to me: 'No, I have a document with the image of Benjamin Franklin, it always comes in handy.'
He showed me his driver's license with the $100 bill slipped next to it.
Naturally, I knew that the police took bribes, but I worried that Boris would meet a policeman who was not corrupt.
'Impossible,' Boris declared, 'to enter the traffic police force, you have to buy your chief's silence.'
If you don't take bribes, how can you buy your chief's silence?
Half of Moscow drivers use illegally bought driving licenses.
Those who try to do things by the book drown in administrative red tape.
For 100 dollars, you can drive in the city without brakes!
Corruption and embezzlement have always existed in Russia, before the October Revolution of Lenin and after.
But never at the record levels seen today.
Everyone accepts bribes, everywhere and for everything.
The only ones who don't accept them are those to whom they're not offered, according to Boris.
Corruption flourishes in most institutions, and the fight against corruption always ends in a catastrophe or abandonment.
The police, prosecutors, customs officers, and even the Kremlin: no one anywhere is immune.
Recently, I was visiting a dacha village in one of Moscow's most beautiful commuter towns.
It was a luxurious place but similar to a gulag with its high-security fences and guards.
Examing the pretentious and poorly decorated houses, I asked who owned them and heard that one belonged to a deputy mayor of Moscow, another to a famous singer, and another to the son of a Moscow prosecutor.
But the most attractive property belonged to a modest tax official.
Corruption now represents a greater threat to Russia than the Chechen war.
In fact, the Chechen war wouldn't have lasted as long if it wasn't led by corrupt generals, officers, officials, and police officers who sell arms and supplies to rebels.
The Russian television recently showed a bus making the shuttle from Grozny to Moscow, the same bus that brought 120 kilograms of explosives to Moscow, used for the Dubrovka theater siege, where so many victims lost their lives during the assault meant to free the hostages.
A female passenger on the bus covered the explosives with a rag soaked in acid to prevent customs dogs from smelling them.
A very unnecessary precaution.
No one controls the buses anymore today.
The driver, who did not know what he was transporting, said he was stopped 50 times along his route, and always for the same reason.
A police officer came up to him asking, "Do you know the price?", and the driver replied, "Of course, I know it", by paying the bribe before leaving.
Without a bribe, the bus would have been delayed for hours at each stop, days for the entire trip.
The war against Chechnya continues endlessly not only because the Chechen rebels have Al Qaïda and all "international terrorism" as allies but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, the army, civilians who accept bribes and thieves, who first tax the Chechen civilians or simply steal their property, sell arms and explosives to terrorists, maps showing where the minefields are and provide the rebels with fake documents.
In May of this year, during the Kaspiisk explosions, the terrorists used arms bought from Russian army officers.
The rebels have modern weapons.
Where do they come from?
In the mountains where the rebels hide, there are no armorer shops.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers fighting the rebels have their own ammunition stocks, from which the weapons are stolen and sold.
And not just weapons: certain young officers sell their own men into slavery.
The Russian corruption has reached catastrophic levels, and yet no fight has been launched against this plague.
Should we punish corruption more harshly?
This would only increase the prices of corruption.
The harsher the punishment, the more you will have to pay to avoid it.
No official wants to fight corruption because they themselves are corrupted.
Thus, those called "simple people" consider this phenomenon with benevolence.
They say of their mayor "yes, of course, he steals, but look at all he's done for the city!"
Ordinary people don't like honest workers either.
Why?
A train ticket costs 100 roubles, but by paying a small bribe, one can travel for 50 roubles.
The traveler and the controller both benefit from this system.
An honest old grandmother told me one day that she had bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The controller stopped her by saying that passengers with a ticket were not admitted to the train!
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you don't want your son to be called up for military service, buy a military clerk to strike your son's name off the list or bribe a doctor to declare him unfit for any military activity.
You can enter any faculty for a certain price, regardless of your references and diplomas.
You can drive drunk, speed, ignore red lights, as long as Ben Franklin is there to offer himself to the police.
Alexander Menchikov, the minister of Peter the Great, had understood the impossibility of winning the fight against corruption.
When the tsar Peter, disgusted by the corruption of Russia, decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menchikov replied to him: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects."
In the centuries passed since, the situation has worsened.
Supprimer la corruption could well leave the State without citizens, but if we do not stop the progress of corruption, citizens will soon be left without a State.
